--------------------------------------------------------------
1. TRANSPORT PRINCIPLE
--------------------------------------------------------------

Consider a cumulative response system in which the loading
density m(r) is determined by a p-Laplacian transport law

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/(p-1)),

where

    g_b(r) = baryonic gravitational field
    g_obs(r) = realised gravitational field.

Define the cumulative stiffness coordinate

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds.

Galaxy outer asymptotics satisfy

    g_b(r) ~ r^(-2)
    g_obs(r) ~ r^(-1)

so that

    g_b g_obs ~ r^(-3).

Thus

    m(r) ~ r^(-3/(p-1)).

The cumulative coordinate becomes

    u(r) ~ ∫ r^(-3/(p-1)) dr.

This integral is logarithmic if and only if

    3/(p-1) = 1.

Hence

    p = 4.

--------------------------------------------------------------
Theorem (Marginal Transport)

Quartic transport (p = 4) uniquely produces marginal cumulative
growth

    u(r) ~ log r,

which corresponds to the loading law

    m(r) ∝ (g_b g_obs)^(1/3).

For p < 4 the cumulative loading converges; for p > 4 it diverges
as a power law. Therefore p = 4 is the unique marginal case. ∎



--------------------------------------------------------------
2. COVARIANT TOY MODEL
--------------------------------------------------------------

Introduce a scalar curvature–memory field

    M(x)

representing the local amplitude of retained geometric loading.

In the galaxy regime

    m(r) ~ M(r).

--------------------------------------------------------------
2.1 Covariant Lagrangian

The minimal action is

    L = √(-g) [ 
        1/2 ∇_μ M ∇^μ M
        − (a/4) M^4
        + b Π M
    ].

where

    Π = curvature overlap invariant.


--------------------------------------------------------------
2.2 Source–response invariant

Define

    Π = sqrt[ (∇_μ Φ_b ∇^μ Φ_b)(a_ν a^ν) ]

where

    Φ_b = baryonic gravitational potential
    a_μ = observer four-acceleration.

In the weak-field static limit

    |∇Φ_b| → g_b
    sqrt(a_μ a^μ) → g_obs

so that

    Π → g_b g_obs.


--------------------------------------------------------------
2.3 Field equation

Variation with respect to M yields

    □M + a M^3 = b Π.

In the quasi-static galaxy regime

    □M << a M^3

so

    M^3 ≈ (b/a) Π.

Thus

    M ∝ (g_b g_obs)^(1/3).

This reproduces the marginal transport law.


--------------------------------------------------------------
3. STATIC SPHERICAL FIELD EQUATION
--------------------------------------------------------------

For a static spherically symmetric configuration

    M = M(r)

the field equation becomes

    (1/r^2)(r^2 M')' + a M^3 = b Π(r).

In galaxies

    Π(r) ≈ g_b(r) g_obs(r).

Hence

    (1/r^2)(r^2 M')' + a M^3 = b g_b g_obs.


--------------------------------------------------------------
3.1 Outer-galaxy solution

With

    g_b ~ GM_b / r^2
    g_obs ~ V_∞^2 / r

we obtain

    Π ~ r^(-3).

The asymptotic solution is

    M(r) = K / r

with

    K = [ (b/a) GM_b V_∞^2 ]^(1/3).

This profile exactly satisfies the field equation because

    (r^2 M')' = 0.


--------------------------------------------------------------
4. CUMULATIVE STIFFNESS COORDINATE
--------------------------------------------------------------

Define

    u(r) = ∫_0^r M(s) ds.

Using the outer solution

    M ~ 1/r

gives

    u(r) ~ K log r.

Thus galaxy dynamics occur in a logarithmically expanding
cumulative coordinate.


--------------------------------------------------------------
5. RESPONSE LAW
--------------------------------------------------------------

Define the normalized response field

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s).

The orbital velocity saturates exponentially in S:

    V(r)/V_∞ = 1 − exp[−S(r)].

This reproduces the observed rotation-curve master curve.


--------------------------------------------------------------
6. IMPLICIT RADIAL ACCELERATION RELATION
--------------------------------------------------------------

Transport implies

    u'(r) = C [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3).

Using

    S = u/u_s

and

    g_obs(r) = V_∞^2 / r (1 − e^{-S})^2

gives the differential equation

    dS/dr =
    A V_∞^(2/3) r^(-1/3) g_b(r)^(1/3) (1 − e^{-S})^(2/3)

where

    A = C/u_s.

Separating variables yields the implicit RAR solution

    F(S(r)) =
    A V_∞^(2/3)
    ∫_0^r s^(-1/3) g_b(s)^(1/3) ds

with

    F(S) = ∫_0^S dσ / (1 − e^{-σ})^(2/3).

Observed acceleration follows from

    g_obs = V_∞^2 / r (1 − e^{-S})^2.


--------------------------------------------------------------
6.1 Weak-response limit

For

    S << 1

the function

    F(S) ~ 3 S^(1/3)

and the resulting relation reduces locally to

    g_obs ∝ g_b^(2 − 3/q)

if

    g_b ~ r^(-q).

Thus the RAR slope depends on the local baryonic gradient.


--------------------------------------------------------------
7. BARYONIC TULLY–FISHER RELATION
--------------------------------------------------------------

At large radius

    M(r) ~ (GM_b V_∞^2)^(1/3) / r.

The cumulative coordinate at the turnover radius becomes

    u(R_s) ~ (GM_b V_∞^2)^(1/3) Λ_s

where

    Λ_s = logarithmic accumulation factor.

If galaxies reach a common saturation threshold

    S(R_s) = 1

then

    u(R_s) ≈ const.

Therefore

    (GM_b V_∞^2)^(1/3) ≈ const.

which implies

    V_∞^4 ∝ G M_b.

Thus the baryonic Tully–Fisher relation emerges as the
global saturation condition of the cumulative transport law.


